g a series of intellectual episodes—from the fifteenth-century Humanism of Lorenzo Valla to the poetry of Emily Dickinson, from Immanuel Kant and Johann Georg Hamann to Friedrich Nietzsche, Franz Kafka, and Paul Celan—Philology of the Flesh considers the far-reaching ramifications of the incarnational metaphor, insisting on the inseparability of form and content, an insistence that allows us to rethink our relation to the concrete languages in which we think and live.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aIncarnationxHistory of doctrines. 0aPhilologyxReligious aspects. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aHermeneutics.  aPhilology.  aPoetics.  aTheology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226572963423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226572963/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles